BackingField is set before the very first property is initialized in C#. This allows you to define values that are used throughout the class, even before any constructor has been called. It is particularly useful for setting up default values or initializing fields that are used across multiple constructors. In your scenario, since you want to initialize `id` and `name`, you can use backing fields in combination with a constructor or static method to achieve this. Here's how you can do it:

```csharp
public class User
{
    private int _id;
    private string _name;

    public User(int id, string name)
    {
        _id = id;
        _name = name;
    }

    // Static method to initialize users
    public static List<User> InitializeUsers()
    {
        return new List<User>
        {
            new User(1, "John Doe"),
            new User(2, "Jane Smith")
        };
    }
}

// Usage
List<User> users = User.InitializeUsers();
```

In this example, `_id` and `_name` are the backing fields for the `Id` and `Name` properties respectively. The `InitializeUsers` method creates a list of `User` objects using these backing fields without needing to call a constructor explicitly. This approach is clean and avoids the need for a separate method just to set initial values.

